Later bronzes of Andrew Carnegie and Robert Collyer adorned the entrance hall of Ilkley Library on its opening in October 1907. #FrancesDarlington grew up in Ilkley, her family lived there from 1885 to 1897 when she began @SladeSchool & her family moved to #Harrogate. #IWD2019 https://t.co/0u5pn0DO2Y

Many of the photographs I am posting were taken by #FrancesDarlington in her studio. This piece, 'The Madonna Della Rosa' (1906-7) was lost for years until Matthew Withey from @HMILeeds found it in the crypt @StWilfHarrogate during research for the exhibition in 2002. #IWD2019 https://t.co/nxaT2FYt4a

Whilst at The South Kensington Schools (@RCA ) #FrancesDarlington stayed at Queen Alexandra House, a residence for #women studying in London, (just opposite @RoyalAlbertHall). This bronze bust of its founder, Sir Francis Cook (1817-1901) was made in 1901. #InternationalWomensDay https://t.co/wBtuvl4rfx

This figure, '10 Day Life Study' c.1900 by #FrancesDarlington was made during her time at the South Kensington Schools, (now @RCA not sure whether that makes her @AlumniRCA). Like 'The Little Sea Maiden' & 'The Magic Crystal' it concentrates upon a female gaze & focus. #IWD2019 https://t.co/oC5DjD9tl9
The Little Sea Maiden (1905) by #FrancesDarlington @LeedsArtGallery - the beautiful gaze lost to the screen here. #InternationalWomensDay2019 #IWD2019 https://t.co/p2M0WoJ9XQ

The Magic Crystal by #FrancesDarlington used electricity as part of its #polychromy. Current whereabouts unknown but it was included in an #ArtsAndCrafts exhibition in #Leeds in 1904. It bears some similarities to The Little Sea Maiden (1905) held by @LeedsArtGallery #IWD2019 https://t.co/cUO2eN30Vu

My favourite works of female sculptor #FrancesDarlington are her works on #Arthurian Legend and the #HolyGrail completed c1907. The panel on the left is in the library at #Harrogate Ladies College and the panel on the right is in St. Mary's Church, Ingleton. #IWD2019 https://t.co/lb9DZJ32vw

The earliest work we have by #FrancesDarlington is a figure of her sister, Emma Dorothy Darlington made in 1896 when Frances was 16 and signed with her trademark little "Dicky" bird - Dickie was her nickname! #InternationalWomensDay #IWD2019 https://t.co/K9IWb1a9AK
I should add that the dates in the title of the exhibition was wrong and based on the evidence we had to hand at the time. Frances' dates are actually 1880-1940.

For #InternationalWomensDay I will be tweeting works by #FrancesDarlington throughout the day. By their fruits shall ye know them! #iwd2019 Here is the first exhibition of her work @MercerGallery #Harrogate in 2003. The elderly lady is her niece! https://t.co/oO5h0kiljJ
